{"questionId":"9067872","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Copper forms two chlorides, copper(I) chloride and copper(II) chloride.</span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">An electrolysis cell was assembled using graphite electrodes and connected as shown.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/412e83336e3f21ee452c765485f785ed63739df7.png\"></span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Write the half-equation for the formation of gas bubbles at electrode 1.</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">2Cl<sup>−</sup> → Cl<sub>2</sub> (g) + 2e<sup>−</sup><br><em><strong>OR</strong></em><br>Cl<sup>−</sup> → <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{1}{2}\"> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </math></span>Cl<sub>2</sub> (g) + e<sup>−</sup> ✔</span></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"> NOTE:&nbsp;Accept e for e<sup>−</sup>.</span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9067872","referenceCode":"19N.2.sl.TZ0.c(ii)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Write the half-equation for the formation of gas bubbles at electrode 1.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c(ii)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Core","Topic 9: Redox processes","9.2 Electrochemical cells","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships","1.1 Introduction to the particulate nature of matter and chemical change","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships","Core","Topic 9: Redox processes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}